{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614081"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:41:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:41:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16340"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16340"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9031"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64800"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9031"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16340"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50234"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2076"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7507"},{"type":"tags","id":"7519"},{"type":"tags","id":"8133"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21482"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21486"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64800"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA patient undergoes fundoscopy. Fundoscopic examination reveals bright red, feathery-edged haemorrhages radiating outward from the optic disc in a flame-shaped pattern.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical location of these haemorrhages?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Vitreous haemorrhage","Nerve fibre layer haemorrhage","Outer retinal layer haemorrhage","Preretinal haemorrhage","Sub-retinal haemorrhage"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe fundoscopic findings described show characteristic flame-shaped or splinter haemorrhages. \u003Cstrong\u003ENerve fibre layer haemorrhages\u003C/strong\u003E have this distinctive appearance because blood tracks along the direction of the retinal nerve fibres, creating a feathery or flame-shaped pattern. These are commonly seen in hypertensive retinopathy and diabetic retinopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitreous haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E appears as a diffuse redness or haziness that obscures the view of the retina. It occurs in the vitreous cavity and does not have a specific shape or pattern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOuter retinal layer haemorrhages\u003C/strong\u003E appear as round, dot-like or blot haemorrhages because the outer retinal layers are arranged differently from the nerve fibre layer. They do not show the characteristic flame-shaped pattern.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPreretinal haemorrhages\u003C/strong\u003E (also called sub-hyaloid haemorrhages) occur between the retina and vitreous. They have a boat-shaped appearance with a flat upper border due to gravity and are typically dark red.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESub-retinal haemorrhages\u003C/strong\u003E occur beneath the retina and appear as dark red, round or irregular patches. They do not show the feathery pattern characteristic of nerve fibre layer haemorrhages.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the anatomical location of retinal haemorrhages is crucial as it can help identify the underlying pathology. The flame-shaped appearance is pathognomonic of nerve fibre layer involvement and is commonly associated with systemic conditions like hypertension and diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nerve fibre layer haemorrhages appear flame-shaped or splinter-like due to blood tracking along retinal nerve fibres","Nerve fibre layer haemorrhages are commonly seen in hypertensive retinopathy and diabetic retinopathy","The appearance and location of retinal haemorrhages help determine their anatomical depth in the retina"],"references":["Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-Kels JM. Human ocular anatomy. Clin Dermatol. 2015 Mar-Apr;33(2):140-6. doi: 10.1016/j.clindermatol.2014.10.006. PMID: 25704934","Au A, Hilely A, Scharf J, Gunnemann F, Wang D, Chehaibou I, Iovino C, Grondin C, Farecki ML, Falavarjani KG, Phasukkijwatana N, Battista M, Borrelli E, Sacconi R, Powell B, Hom G, Greenlee TE, Conti TF, Ledesma-Gil G, Teke MY, Choudhry N, Fung AT, Krivosic V, Baek J, Lee MY, Sugiura Y, Querques G, Peiretti E, Rosen R, Lee WK, Yannuzzi LA, Zur D, Loewenstein A, Pauleikhoff D, Singh R, Modi Y, Hubschman JP, Ip M, Sadda S, Freund KB, Sarraf D. Relationship Between Nerve Fiber Layer Hemorrhages and Outcomes in Central Retinal Vein Occlusion. Invest Ophthalmol Vis Sci. 2020 May 11;61(5):54. doi: 10.1167/iovs.61.5.54. PMID: 32460316; PMCID: PMC7405700.","Sahinoglu-Keskek N, Cevher S, Ergin A. Analysis of subconjunctival hemorrhage. Pak J Med Sci. 2013 Jan;29(1):132-4. doi: 10.12669/pjms.291.2802. PMID: 24353524; PMCID: PMC3809196."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50234"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16340"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50234","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.co